{
    "attributes": {
        "action": "Make flexible working requests available to all with presumption of approval",
        "additional_details": "Under current legislation, workers do not have the right to request flexible working until they have completed 26 weeks of service. There is currently no obligation to accept a request and these can be rejected for a number of reasons.\r\n \r\nThe current legislation causes a substantial barrier to many groups such as; women, carers and those with disabilities. As many roles only consider applicants that can work full time.\r\n \r\nA day 1 right would remove this barrier and help to remove the gender pay gap.",
        "background": "Give employees the right to request flexible working from day 1 of employment and create a presumption in favour of flexible working by placing the burden on employers to demonstrate that a role is unsuitable for flexible working, including part-time hours, annualised hours and job sharing.",
